seal     : Philips pitched the CD-i not as a games console but as an interactive multimedia player for the living room — encyclopaedias, music, edutainment — built on a 68000-family CPU. It's best remembered, unfairly to its intent, for a clutch of dire Zelda and Mario games made under a licensing deal with Nintendo.
